User Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64; rv:135.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/135.0  Steps to reproduce:  Set up a bunch of container tabs, one for each color, and then create a new tab with the black container selected.   Actual results:  Other tabs show a vertical stripe next to them with the color of the container--this doesn't happen for black tabs   Expected results:  Thin vertical black stripe like with every other container color

The [Bugbug](https://github.com/mozilla/bugbug/) bot thinks this bug should belong to the 'Firefox::Tabbed Browser' component, and is moving the bug to that component. Please correct in case you think the bot is wrong.

I can reproduce this issue using Firefox 135.0a1 and Firefox 134.0b10 on macOS 13 while using Dark Theme.  On Windows 10 the horizontal line is changed to light grey as it does when you change the theme to Firefox Alpenglow (dark).  Is this what you are seeing too?

(In reply to Oana Botisan, Desktop QA from comment #2) > I can reproduce this issue using Firefox 135.0a1 and Firefox 134.0b10 on macOS 13 while using Dark Theme.  > On Windows 10 the horizontal line is changed to light grey as it does when you change the theme to Firefox Alpenglow (dark).  > Is this what you are seeing too?  I have not tested on Windows; I have been able to reproduce it on MacOS and several Linux distributions. I haven't tested with an X-window server based DWM, but it happens in Gnome and Sway on Wayland. On a dark theme, the line is visible as a pale almost-white color. I'm curious if that color just so happens to be identical to the light-theme background?

Now that's interesting. I just switched back from the dark theme to the light theme and ... the black sidebar appears for those container tabs exactly as I would expect. My guess here is that when it's first set up, it assumes you're in a dark-mode without checking, and sets it to the dark-mode version of that tab color, which just happens to be invisible on light themes?

The severity field is not set for this bug. :niklas, could you have a look please?  For more information, please visit [BugBot documentation](https://wiki.mozilla.org/BugBot#workflow.2Fno_severity_ni.py).

Created attachment 9446395 Bug 1938707 - Update identity-color-toolbar color r=#desktop-theme-reviewers   On system themes, using `toolbar-field-color` for the `identity-color-toolbar` results in a container indicator that's the same color as the tab. But for every other theme, `--toolbar-field-color: light-dark(rgb(21, 20, 26), rgb(251, 251, 254));`. This patch ensures we do the same container indicator color for all themes.

Created attachment 9444819 testcase 1  STR: 1. Load attached testcase.  EXPECTED RESULTS: Black-bordered squares should be all filled with lime (plus green circles in the 2nd and 3rd ones). No red should be visible.  ACTUAL RESULTS: Only the last rect is filled with lime. The rest of the squares are mostly red.  NOTES: It looks like we're ignoring the min/max-height constraints when resolving `width:min-content` from the aspect ratio and the specified `height:5px`. So we end up with a min-content width of 5px (derived from the specified and **unclamped** `height`), even though we actually have definite min/max constraints that we should probably be applying before transferring the height.  This doesn't seem to be a recent regression; I just ran across it when writing testcases for the CSS `stretch` keyword (which hits this problem as well, though it's not unique to `stretch`.)
Note, we do this correctly in the last square, which is a div with `aspect-ratio: 1/1`.  So it looks like it's only the replaced-element sizing codepath that has this broken, perhaps...

For comparison: * Chromium gives EXPECTED RESULTS. * WebKit (epiphany) gives EXPECTED RESULTS just for the first square (the ``), whereas they give a different set of broken-results for the second and 3rd boxes (the `svg`/``) -- they size the replaced element to be 22px wide there for some reason.

Created attachment 9444820 testcase 2 (with 'max-height')  Here's a testcase where we've got a large specified `height` that's constrained by a `max-height`. We seem to be transferring the large/unclamped `height` when determining our `width`, when we should not be doing so.

Created attachment 9444822 testcase 3 (now using 'width:max-content') -- we get this one correct  Here's a testcase that's identical to the previous one, but I've simply changed `width:min-content` to `width:max-content`.  That makes us get this correct (and produce the correct smaller width on the replaced element).  (So right now Firefox is essentially behaving as if the min-content width of these elements is wider than the max-content width, which doesn't really make sense. :) )

Currently we have a background resource usage test: https://searchfox.org/mozilla-central/source/testing/performance/android-resource  This test is loading a single url to a single tab and takes the app to the background and records values for the resource usage. In the scope of this ticket, more complex testing scenarios will be implemented.
:kaya, can you provide some info on what these more complex background tests should be?

I was thinking about two different paths here: 1. Focused on the resource consumption of content processes 2. Focused on the resource consumption of main process  I think we can still track Chrome for 1st option and have comparisons. For 2nd option, I imagine that'd be Fenix-specific test cases, though could still be applied to Chrome. Also worth mentioning, I believe integrating the proxy service for website snapshot usage would be really helpful while we are implementing the complex scenarios as we would need to deal with less variables. The shell scripts I had already has the capability to add tabs, scroll up/down, load urls etc. But when a website has cookie banner dialogs etc, then the gestures' application gets tricky as the dialogs get the focus on themselves on the screen.    For 1: - Loading more than 1 page (current test loads a single url). - Creating more than 1 tab and loading pages. - Back and forward navigations between pages (& tabs).   For 2: - Navigating through the tree-dot menu (eg. to Bookmarks, Downloads, Settings etc. and navigating back.). This might help visualize the memory leaks or the amount getting deallocated etc.    There's also a case with the Extensions, but may easily fall under a separate ticket. That would be to measure the performance of some of very popular extensions in case they regress any perfomance issues. Not sure how you'd feel about that and whether it is worth adding to our infrastructure.

I've seen a similar discussion elsewhere but only found Bug 1699686. In short, set the MIPS_UNALIGNED environment variable to ignore errors regarding unaligned access on the mips64 simulator.
After setting this environment variable, it crashes as: ``` Assertion failure: cx_->hadResourceExhaustion(), at /home/fuzzer/gecko-devlatest/js/src/jit/WarpOracle.cpp:206 ```

(In reply to gal1ium from comment #3) > After setting this environment variable, it crashes as: > ``` > Assertion failure: cx_->hadResourceExhaustion(), at /home/fuzzer/gecko-devlatest/js/src/jit/WarpOracle.cpp:206 > ```  Looks like the CodeGenerator incorrectly believes that `0 % -16` should be -0.0, as the comment assumes that it follows the behavior of division, since `0 / -16` is indeed -0.0.  But there's more to this bug. Natively running the same PoC on mips64 hardware doesn't successfully produce the same assertion failure, and setting IONFLAGS to `bailouts,bl-bails` doesn't show me consecutive `modi` bails of BailoutKind `TranspiledCacheIR`, unlike the simulator. I may need to dig deeper before sending a patch here.

(In reply to Xuan Chen from comment #4) > I may need to dig deeper before sending a patch here.  Increasing the inner loop count to 500000 successfully caused the same failure on my Loongson 3B4000. Great.

(I have no permission to leave comments on Bug 1684730, so I'll post my findings here)  At BaselineCodeGen.cpp, we've got some load operations with no alignment handling and an offset of 1 byte: ```C++ static void LoadUint16Operand(MacroAssembler& masm, Register dest) {   Register pc = LoadBytecodePC(masm, dest);   masm.load16ZeroExtend(Address(pc, sizeof(jsbytecode)), dest); }  static void LoadInt32Operand(MacroAssembler& masm, Register dest) {   Register pc = LoadBytecodePC(masm, dest);   masm.load32(Address(pc, sizeof(jsbytecode)), dest); }  static void LoadInt32OperandSignExtendToPtr(MacroAssembler& masm, Register pc,                                             Register dest) {   masm.load32SignExtendToPtr(Address(pc, sizeof(jsbytecode)), dest); } ``` I may need other's assistance on how I should fix it, or at least tamper with it...
Created attachment 9445645 modi-signed-int32.js  PoC with a shorter loop

The `cx_->hadResourceExhaustion()` assertion is designed to catch performance issues involving repeated bailouts.   While running in baseline, we attach inline cache stubs for a variety of operations (including the JSOp::Mod in `zero % -0x10`). In this case, I would expect the CacheIR to look like this: ``` GuardToInt32                  inputId 0 GuardToInt32                  inputId 1 Int32ModResult                lhsId 0, rhsId 1 ReturnFromIC    ``` Looking at the code we generate [for Int32ModResult](https://searchfox.org/mozilla-central/source/js/src/jit/CacheIRCompiler.cpp#3384-3388), `0 % -16` will produce +0. This appears to match the spec (step 5 [here](https://tc39.es/ecma262/#sec-numeric-types-number-remainder)).  When we Ion-compile, we take this CacheIR and convert it into MIR. Int32ModResult should be lowered to MMod in WarpCacheIRTranspiler](https://searchfox.org/mozilla-central/source/js/src/jit/WarpCacheIRTranspiler.cpp#3222-3225). It should eventually be lowered by calling LowerModI [here](https://searchfox.org/mozilla-central/rev/94c62970ba2f9c40efd5a4f83a538595425820d9/js/src/jit/Lowering.cpp#2398). That will generate some LIR, which will eventually produce some code. Somewhere in that code, a bailout check is being generated. My best guess is that we create an LModI and end up [here](https://searchfox.org/mozilla-central/rev/94c62970ba2f9c40efd5a4f83a538595425820d9/js/src/jit/mips-shared/CodeGenerator-mips-shared.cpp#582-629). Depending on how optimization proceeded, it looks like that code might bail out if the lhs is 0 and the rhs is negative. In that case, we will (eventually) throw away the Ion code and return to baseline. We expect to be able to recompile better code later that will be able to handle the unexpected input. But we don't change the CacheIR, because the baseline CacheIR compiler already handles this case correctly. So the exact same thing will happen next time we compile, and we will end up bailing out repeatedly.  This is bad for performance, which is why we added this assertion. I suspect the fix is to change the code in `CodeGenerator::visitModI` to more closely match other architectures.  I see the [same incorrect comment](https://searchfox.org/mozilla-central/search?q=0%2FX+%28with+X+%3C+0%29+is+bad+because+both+of+these+values+*should*+be&path=&case=false&regexp=false) in the loong64 and riscv64 code generators, so it might need fixing there too.  Hope this helps!
